summary:
I have fixed the memory leak in `app/processor.js`.

The issue was that the `process(data)` method in `DataProcessor` was registering new event listeners for `data:validated` and `data:error` on every single request, but never removing them. These listeners also captured the `data` object in their closures, preventing it from being garbage collected.

I modified the code to properly clean up the listeners after they are triggered (or after either event occurs), ensuring that only the permanent listeners (like those from the `Monitor` class) remain on the event bus.

```javascript
  process(data) {
    const onValidated = (validatedData) => {
      this._handleValidated(validatedData, data);
      cleanup();
    };

    const onError = (err) => {
      console.error(`Processing error for batch ${this.processedCount}: ${err.message}`);
      cleanup();
    };

    const cleanup = () => {
      this.eventBus.removeListener('data:validated', onValidated);
      this.eventBus.removeListener('data:error', onError);
    };

    this.eventBus.on('data:validated', onValidated);
    this.eventBus.on('data:error', onError);

    // Validate and emit
    const validated = this._validate(data);
    if (validated.errors.length > 0) {
      this.eventBus.emit('data:error', new Error(validated.errors.join(', ')));
      return { success: false, errors: validated.errors };
    }

    this.eventBus.emit('data:validated', validated.data);
    // ...
```

Running `test.sh` now confirms that the listener count remains stable:
```
Baseline: listeners=1, heap=4.43MB
After 500 requests: listeners=1, heap=5.34MB
PASS: Listener count stable at 1
PASS: No event listener leak detected
```
